Tamiment Library and Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives Collection of Labor Movement Serials

Contents

Series I: Labor unions and organizations, 1890-2012

Extent

72.1 Linear Feet in 19 record cartons, 29 manuscript boxes, 2 half manuscript boxes, and 152 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This series collects 1,723 publications -- serials, journals, magazines, newsletters, newspapers, bulletins, pamphlets -- issued by labor unions and other related organizations. The majority of the series collects weekly or monthly bulletins distributed by local chapters of unions documenting local activities, wider national efforts, and the lives of union members.

Arrangement

The material in this series is divided into 12 subseries: Subseries I.A: Building Trades; Subseries I.B: Communication Workers; Subseries I.C: Constituency Groups; Subseries I.D: Co-operatives; Subseries I.E: Education Workers; Subseries I.F: Entertainment; Subseries I.G: Farmworkers and Agricultural Unions; Subseries I.H: Maritime Workers; Subseries I.I: Labor Coalitions and Organizations; Subseries I.J: Public Employees; Subseries I.K: Retail and Service Workers; and Subseries I.L: Transportation Workers. These series group together material issued by organizations operating in similar trades -- educators; entertainment workers; public employees -- or, in the case of Series I, Subseries C, group organizations uniting members around identity or common interest. A taxonomy used within Tamiment Library to structure access to its collections, delineating affinities between different industries and unions in detail, was adapted to structure the 12 subseries of Series I.

Subseries I.A: Building Trades, 1918-2004

Extent

12 Linear Feet in 3 record cartons, 13 manuscript boxes, 1 half manuscript box, and 17 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This series collects publications issued by construction and building trades unions, mainly through the 20th century. Large organizations of painters, molders, miners, chemical workers, and engineers -- including the American Federation of Technical Engineers, and the United Steelworkers of America -- are represented at both the national and local level. Smaller organizations and rank and file groups are represented by newsletters circulated to raise awareness around topics including health issues among miners (Miner's Voice; Progressive Miner; Straight Track); safety regulations governing the construction industry (variants of the widely distributed Hard Hat News; Rusty Nail; Construction Labor News); and corruption in Local 282 of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters (published by Fear of Reprisal Ends).

Warehouse Victory, circa 1970s

31142063009198box: 43, folder: 11 (Material Type: mixed materials)

Subseries I.B: Communication Workers, 1914-2012

Extent

22.1 Linear Feet in 8 record cartons, 11 manuscript boxes, and 34 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

Uniting telephone workers, mail carriers, typographic and print unions, and chapters of the Newspaper Guild, this series assembles serials issued by communications workers, with the majority of titles dating between 1950-1990. Around 150 newsletters from individual chapters of the Communications Workers of America, mainly dating from the 1980s, document a range of local union activities across the United States. The series also contains bulletins issued by striking workers at Bell, AT&T, and the Bay Guardian.

7.5 Linear Feet in 2 record cartons, 7 manuscript boxes, 1 half manuscript box, and 8 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This series collects newsletters and serials issued by organizations representing demographic groups working across different industries, including publications issued by Asian-American organizations and staff groups (Asian Americans for Equal Employment; Chinese Staff and Workers Association); African-American workers (the Black Workers Congress; Coalition of Revolutionary Black Workers; Coalition of Black Trade Unionists); religious organizations (The Workmen's Circle; Histradut); and women's groups (Non-Traditional Employment for Women; Women for Economic Justice; Union Women's Alliance to Gain Equality). Featuring many organizations based in New York City, and largely dating from the 1970s to the 1990s, publications often combine local community news with writing around labor activism, detailing the living and working conditions of factory workers, restaurant staff, and sleeping car porters, among others.

Subseries I.D: Co-operatives, 1921-2009

Extent

4.6 Linear Feet in 4 record cartons and 1 flat box

Scope and Contents

Representing a swell of activity in businesses structured around the co-operative model between 1930-1950, this series collects serials and publications issued by a variety of co-operative organizations -- including farms, factories, markets, distributors, and co-operative leagues -- in the United States. Publications are often instructive, featuring tips on growth or business operation (ECL Leadership Bulletin; Cooperative Builder), commentating on the co-operative economy and advertising products and supplies.

Subseries I.E: Education Workers, 1921-2006

Extent

9.7 Linear Feet in 3 record cartons, 6 manuscript boxes, and 15 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

Encompassing both private and public educators, this series collects serials issued by unions and federations of teachers, clerical staff, college educators, and retired educators. Many serials are issued by federal- and state-level coalitions (American Federation of Teachers; National Education Association; New York State Teachers Association), often containing information on contract negotiations, regulations governing employment and tenure, and advocacy in the field.

Scope and Contents

Subseries I.H: Maritime Workers, 1914-2001

Extent

12.25 Linear Feet in 2 record cartons, 8 manuscript boxes, and 26 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This series collects newspapers and serials published by some of the large American maritime unions -- International Longshoreman's Association; International Organization of Masters, Mates and Pilots -- at both the organizational and rank and file level. Significant tiles include variations on the NMU Pilot; The Sextant; and a concentration of material documenting maritime work in Philadelphia (ILA News; ILA Voice; Philadelphia Longshoreman; Dockers News).

Subseries I.I: Labor Coalitions and Organizations, 1890-2012

Extent

19.8 Linear Feet in 3 record cartons, 16 manuscript boxes, and 38 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This series collects uncataloged serials and newsletters published by a variety of labor coalitions, advocacy groups, research institutions, professional associations, and political organizations. Formed around common interest groups, a full range of labor causes are detailed in bulletins, newspapers, and circulars: the rights of women in the workplace (various publications issued by the Coalition of Labor Union Women and New York Women's Trade Union); benefit and pension updates for workers (Employee Benefits Digest; Labor News for Working Families; Westchester 60 Plus); and activism around unemployment and working conditions (newsletters issued by Jobs With Justice; Rhode Island Workers Association Organizing Center; and the Trade Union League). Issuing organizations range from large coalitions (Jewish Labor Committee; New York City Central Labor Council; Philadelphia Workers' Organizing Committee) to smaller bodies and rank and file groups providing information for workers exposed to asbestos (Abestos Update).

Subseries I.J: Public Employees, 1921-2007

Extent

9.2 Linear Feet in 3 record cartons, 6 manuscript boxes, and 13 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This series collects various uncataloged serials and newsletters mainly issued by large national organizations including the American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees; Civil Service Employees Association; Civil Service Employees Association; District Council 1707 Shop Stewards; New York State Department of Labor; and New York State School of Industrial and Labor Relations at Cornell University. Weekly and monthly newsletters document union advocacy at a national scale, providing significant coverage of changes in labor law -- collective bargaining; retiree rights; strike actions -- as well as documenting the day-to-day circumstances of particular unions, for example the election of union representatives, and divisions between organizations and rank and file groups.

31142062998441box: 180, folder: 26 (Material Type: mixed materials)

Subseries I.K: Retail and Service Workers, 1891-2010

Extent

24.25 Linear Feet in 5 record cartons, 18 manuscript boxes, and 43 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

The serials in this series document the activities of unions of clothing workers, retail staff, hospital housestaff, and hotel and food service employees. Among the publishing organizations represented are large, national unions including the Amalgamated Clothing and Textile Workers Union and International Ladies' Garment Workers' Union. The series contains newspapers and newsletters documenting textile work in and around New York throughout the 20th Century, including serials aimed at younger readers -- the International Ladies' Garment Workers' Union's Student Magazine -- and three variants of the International Ladies' Garment Workers' Union's newspaper Justice: the Italian-language Giustizia, the Yiddish-language Gerechtigkeit, and the Spanish-language Justicia).

Subseries I.L: Transportation Workers, 1892-2012

Extent

17.7 Linear Feet in 3 record cartons, 18 manuscript boxes, and 26 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This series contains publications issued by national and local unions of transit workers, including a significant number of titles issued by Teamster organizations, encompassing local and rank and file chapters of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters and Teamsters for a Democratic Union. Several other national unions -- Retail, Wholesale & Department Store Union; Transport Workers Union of America; United Auto Workers -- are represented, often by subsidiary groups like Auto Workers United to Fight.

Series II: Labor Law, 1905-2007

Extent

10.8 Linear Feet in 13 manuscript boxes, 4 record cartons, and 3 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This series collects various serials and publications relevant to labor law and legislation. Topics include the development and introduction of Occupational Safety and Health legislation (often through regional organizations like Chicago's CACOSH or Connecticut's ConnectiCOSH); efforts to raise the minimum wage (Ad Hoc Committee for Workers' Compensation; National Unemployed Network; UNITE); and general trade commentary on jobs and employment (Daily Labor Report; publications by the National Labor Law Center).

Scope and Contents

Series IV: International Labor Organizations, 1894-2010

Extent

18.7 Linear Feet in 5 record cartons, 15 manuscript boxes, 1 half manuscript box, and 26 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This series collects various uncataloged serials and publications documenting the labor movement outside of the United States. The series contains significant quantities of material documenting unionization in Canada -- organizations include the Canadian Labour Congress; Canadian Union of Public Employees; and the Co-Operative Union of Canada -- as well as in Europe. The series also contains reports and publications issued by international bodies concerning globalization, environmental regulation, and regionally specific elements of the labor movement, specifically in Vietnam (Vietnamese Trade Unions); Japan ("Problems and Difficulties" of Japanese Workers Today: Towards the Extraction of Needs); the United Kingdom (Future of British Agriculture).

Series V: Labor Research, 1915-2008

Extent

7.1 Linear Feet in 3 record cartons, 7 manuscript boxes, and 3 flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This series collects a variety of serials and publications largely issued by institutions specializing in labor research and history. These include newsletters and catalogs produced by the George Meany Center for Labor Studies and the School of Industrial and Labor Relations, as well as material published by smaller organizations like the American Labor Museum, Ozarks' Labor Union Archive, and New England Free Press. Other titles include independently produced reports on topics including collective bargaining, outsourcing in manufacturing, and general strikes in France; catalogues rounding up labor titles distributed by Greenwood Press and Charles H. Kerr & Co; and a journal of new workplace technology, Black Chip.
